<div id="review_2332692664" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2332692664" />
    <a title="Elena Todisco" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57071284-elena-todisco"><img alt="Elena Todisco" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1466701817p2/57071284.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2332692664?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena Todisco" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena Todisco" href="/user/show/57071284-elena-todisco">Elena Todisco</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2332692664" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3645984995014548055">Emotional. <br/>I&apos;ve never appreciated Baricco, to be completely honest, and mostly because of his writing. A witness is my &quot;Ocean sea&quot; copy left with a bookmark at page 8 and never ever re-opened again. This book, although, is a rare gem. I&apos;m persuaded that the reason why I&apos;ve liked it so much is because it is not a novel, but a monologue, a piéce. What sounds over-dramatic, pretentious, and barely bearable in a novel results in the perfect theatre-style. There is nothing I would change in this &quot;boo</span>
  <span id="freeText3645984995014548055" style="display:none">Emotional. <br />I've never appreciated Baricco, to be completely honest, and mostly because of his writing. A witness is my "Ocean sea" copy left with a bookmark at page 8 and never ever re-opened again. This book, although, is a rare gem. I'm persuaded that the reason why I've liked it so much is because it is not a novel, but a monologue, a piéce. What sounds over-dramatic, pretentious, and barely bearable in a novel results in the perfect theatre-style. There is nothing I would change in this "book", from the plot to the emotions Novecento is able to carve from your stone heart. <br />If you don't like Baricco, give Novecento the chance to be the exception that proves the rule.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3645984995014548055" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


